history.content: Given that you're proficient in C (and not just Python) and that you have some Java background, you should be fine if you put in the time to (re)learn language stuff that you've forgotten. The class isn't that heavy on data structures that *aren't covered in the course lectures* so that shouldn't be a problem either.

I'm thinking of taking CS 186 next semester, likely P/NP. I've hard the class is a good amount of work, especially once homeworks are released. I'm worried I'm going to get absolutely overwhelmed by the course simply because I haven't touched Java since I took CS61B in Fall 2016 (so 3.5 years :') ), and my comfort with data structures is less than stellar.

I'm a senior in EECS and this will be my final semester. My academic path was definitely more straight through the middle of EECS, and most of my interest lies in embedded software and numerical computing. I'm perfectly comfortable with C and Python. Alongside, I'll be taking CS 194-26 (Comp Photo), and a natural science elective which may or may not be really difficult/time consuming.

I'm definitely interested in the material covered in 186, and also want to practice my Java, data structures, and general coding skills. Does it sound doable given my skill level? Obviously I can take it P/NP, but I still want to put a reasonable amount of time in and get something out of the course. Also, what is the workload for 194-26 (Comp Photo) like?

Thanks!
history.subject: Taking 186 With Poor Java and Data Structures Skills
